{"OwnerUser":{"UpVotes":"0", "WebsiteUrl":"", "Location":"New York, United States", "Id":"478", "DownVotes":"0", "AccountId":"1015276", "Views":"1", "Reputation":"31", "CreationDate":"2011-11-03T04:20:38.637", "DisplayName":"Huoxingwen", "LastAccessDate":"2013-02-27T22:08:58.790", "AboutMe":""}, "comments":[], "Body":"<p>Wiktionary gives Thai <a href=\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E0%B8%AB%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%A1%E0%B8%B0\" rel=\"nofollow\">hima</a> as having Sanskrit origin, which is directly cognate to the Slavic reflex. See <a href=\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Appendix%3aList_of_Proto-Indo-European_roots/%C7%B5%CA%B0\" rel=\"nofollow\">this appendix</a> for more reflexes. \"Himalaya\" also comes directly from Sanskrit (see that wiktionary entry). So yes, the Sanskrit reflex is squarely Indo-European.</p>\n", "Id":"2713", "ParentId":"2711", "CreationDate":"2012-10-19T18:39:09.093", "Score":"3", "PostTypeId":"2", "OwnerUserId":"478", "LastActivityDate":"2012-10-19T18:39:09.093", "CommentCount":"3"}